"},{"description":"Digital object identifier "}],"resourceInfo":{"abstract":"The tug Western Mariner ran aground on March 21, 2022, in Neva Strait north of Sitka, Alaska, resulting in a discharge of the tug's diesel fuel into marine waters.  Cumulatively throughout the incident, more than 10 square kilometers of marine waters likely experienced some degree of diesel sheening.  Various natural resources under the trusteeship of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and other state and federal agencies were at risk of injury.  The Natural Resource Trustees (U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, Bureau of Indian Affairs, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, U.S. Forest Service, and the Alaska Departments of Environmental Conservation, Fish and Game, Law, and Natural Resources) initiated the preassessment phase of a natural resource damage assessment to evaluate whether the development of a natural resource damages claim was warranted for this incident.  The Trustees collected, or will collect, environmental samples and other data to inform that determination, in accordance with federal regulations for natural resource damage assessment and restoration (NRDAR) under the Oil Pollution Act (15 CFR Part 990).  The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service sponsored the chemical analysis of environmental samples collected in March and May 2022, so these data are included in this data management plan.  The Trustee group resampled the 2022 sites in March 2023, but those efforts and chemical analyses were not lead or sponsored, respectively, by USFWS funds and thus are not included in this DMP but will be managed by NOAA.Data records being managed and archived by NOAA can be accessed from their Western Mariner website:
